Estimating the FoI from the PR

Including: pr2foi, foi2pr, pr2ar, ar2pr, pr2ar, ar2pr

David Smith

2/21/2022

For a more general guide to the estimation utilities of RAMP, see Estimation.html

.

The pr2foi or pr2ar algorithms translate data about the PR into an estimate of exposure using a mechanistic model defined over a state space, \(\cal X\), and a dynamical cohort model:
\[\frac{d{\cal X}}{da}.\] Here, we are assuming that \(h\) is constant over time, so we are evaluating the static patterns.

Here, we present a prototype based on an old published paper. In Variants, we present a list of other functions.

FoI and AR

foi2ar= function(h,D=1){
  1-exp(-h/D)
}
ar2foi = function(ar,D=1){
  -log(1-ar)*D
}

This code demonstrates the two functions are each others inverses.

ar2foi(foi2ar(.1, 10), 10)
foi2ar(ar2foi(.1, 10), 10)

Pseudocode

  • Pass a set of triplets \((a,X,N)\) to a function where

    • \(a\) is the age

    • \(X(a)\) is the number P. falciparum positive by LM or RDT

    • \(N(a)\) is the number sampled.

  • Using a model that predicts the proportion positive by LM or RDT by age, \(x\left(a|h\right)\), computes the log-likelihood of the FoI \(h\) given \(a\), \(x\), and \(N\), \[{\cal L}(h) = X \log x(a|h) + (N-X) \log (1-x(a|h))\]

  • Maximize the likelihood of \(h\).

Generic

foi2pr = function(h,a,Par){
  UseMethod("foi2pr", Par)
}
pr2foi_optimize = function(X,a,N,Par){
  lik_h = function(h, a, X, N, Par) {
    ppr = foi2pr(h,a,Par)
    -sum(X*log(ppr) + (N-X)*log(1-ppr)) 
  }
  optimize(lik_h, c(0,80/365), a=a, X=X, N=N, Par=Par)$minimum
}

Pull & Grab

.

This function is from an analysis done in the 1970s:

  • Pull, J.H., and Grab, B. (1974). A simple epidemiological model for evaluating the malaria inoculation rate and the risk of infection in infants. Bull. World Health Organ. 51, 507–516.

The equation predicting PfPR by age is a slightly modified version of the Ross-Macdonald model: \[\frac{dx}{da} = h(k-x) -rx.\] The paramter \(k\) is an artificial ceiling on the \(x\).

foi2pr.pg= function(h,a,Par){with(Par,{
  h*k/(h+r)*(1-exp(-(h+r)*a))
})}
makePar_pg = function(r=1/200, k=1){ 
  Par.pg= list() 
  Par.pg$r = r
  Par.pg$k = k
  class(Par.pg) <- "pg"
  return(Par.pg) 
}
Par.pg = makePar_pg()
